Everything about this piece speaks of contentment.  The intent expression of a woman doing needlework is well-expressed using light, and shadow on her cheek.  The lace head covering and ornate chair  speak of prviledge, as do the white gloves discarded behind the chair leg.  Though her face and hands show age, and I can clearly see white hair roots, most of her hair is black.  She can afford hair coloring.   The spinning wheel would indicate that she didn't have to depend on anyone for yarn.  The rug looks like it was woven from many yarns--perhaps her yarn leftovers.  The dress looks to be handmade linen, but the shading on the right side makes it look dirty.  A well-bred woman wouldn't be sitting in a dirty dress.The darkened walls look very calming, but it is the rug of many colors that really unites the piece.
